Short Answer Questions

1.What is the difference between a nerve and an axon?

1.What is the difference between a nerve and an axon?

An axon is the long thread-like part of a neuron thatcarried action potentials to other neurons.

A nerve is a collection of many of different axons.

2.What is the difference between efferent and afferentnerves? At what part of the spinal cord do the efferentand afferent nerves join the CNS?

2.What is the difference between efferent and afferentnerves? At what part of the spinal cord do the efferentand afferent nerves join the CNS?

Efferent (motor) nerves carry signal from the CNS. Theyjoin the CNS primarily via the ventral (anterior) root.

Afferent (sensory) nerves carry signals to the CNS. Theyjoin the CNS primarily via the dorsal (posterior) root.

3.How many pairs of spinal nerves are there? How arethey named?

3.How many pairs of spinal nerves are there? How arethey named?

There are 31 pairs of spinal nerves. They are namedaccording to the spinal segment in which they exit/enterthe spinal cord. So, cervical (C1-C8), thoracic (T1-T12),lumbar (L1-L5), sacral (S1-S5) and coccygeal (Co1).

4.What is a dermatome? What is a myotome?

4.What is a dermatome? What is a myotome?

A dermatome is an area of skin that is mainly suppliedby a single spinal nerve.

A myotome is the group of muscles that a single spinalnerve innervates.

How would aspinal cordinjury affect thedermatomesand myotomes?

5.Define gyri, sulci and fissures.

5.Define gyri, sulci and fissures.

Gyri are ridges in the cerebral cortex

Sulci are depressions or furrows in the cerebral cortex

Fissures are deep furrows or a natural division

Longer answer questions

1.Describe three functions of the cerebrospinal fluid.

1.Describe three function of the cerebrospinal fluid?

  • Functions of CSF
    • Buoyancy
      • Allows brain to attain considerable size without beingimpaired by its own weight
      • If brain rested heavily on floor of cranium, pressure would killthe nervous tissue
    • Protection
      • Protects brain from striking cranium when head is jolted
    • Chemical stability
      • Flow of CSF rinses away metabolic wastes from nervous tissueandhomeostaticallyregulates chemical environment

1.Explain the flow of CSF through the brain includingthe role of the

  • Choroid plexus
  • Ventricles
  • Median and Lateral apertures
  • Subarachnoid space
  • Arachnoid granulations
  • Venous sinuses

1.Explain the flow of CSF through the brain including therole of the

  • Choroid plexusCSF is produced via filtration of bloodplasma
  • Ventricleslateral, 3rdand 4thventricles contain choroidplexuses to produce CSF. The CFS descends throughventricles.
  • Median and Lateral aperturesprovides access for the CSFto the outer (pial) surface of the brain in the subarachnoidspace.
  • Subarachnoid spaceCSF baths the outer surface of thebrain in the subarachnoid space.
  • Arachnoid granulationsCSF enters the venous sinusthrough these apertures.
  • Venous sinusesCSF mixes with blood where productscatabolism can be disposed off.
  1. Explain how this flow serves the three functions of theCSF.
  2. Circulation occurs over the entire inner and outer brainsurface, to give it buoyancy, protection from striking thecranium and to absorb metabolic waste from all braintissue. Products catabolism/metabolism are disposed offin the blood after entering the venous sinuses (lungs andkidneys).

3.Explain the relationship of the brainstem to thecerebrum, cerebellum and spinal cord. At a high levelsummarise its functions of the brainstem.

3.Explain the relationship of the brainstem to the cerebrum,cerebellum and spinal cord. At a high level summarise itsfunctions of the brainstem.

  • The brainstem connects the spinal cord to the cerebrumall information travelling between the two must pastthrough brainstem.
  • Likewise it is the major conduit for informationtransmission to and from the cerebellum, from the spinalcord and cerebrum.
  • It plays an important role in integrating and pre-processing informationenrouteto the cortex andcerebellum from the spinal cord. And in transcribing andregulating descending information to the body.
  • It also plays a critical role in regulating many unconsciousprocesses such as cardiovascular, respiratory, and painsensitivity control.

Supplementary Questions

1.Describe the following anatomicallocations/directions and mark them on thefollowing diagram

    • Rostral and Caudal
    • Dorsal and Ventral
    • Inferior and Superior
    • Anterior and Posterior
    • Medial and Lateral

1.Describe the following anatomical locations/directions

    • Rostral and Caudal
      • Rostral is towards the head
      • Caudal is towards the tail
      • Be aware that the rostro-caudal neuroaxis can rotate
        • In humans the longitudinal axis of the forebrain is different to the spinal cord
    • Dorsal and Ventral
      • Dorsal is back (above/up for quadrupeds)
      • Ventral is front (below/down for quadrupeds)
    • Inferior and Superior
      • Inferior is below
      • Superior is above
    • Anterior and Posterior
      • Anterior is towards the front
      • Posterior is towards the back
    • Medial and Lateral
      • Medial is towards the midline
      • Lateral is towards the outside
